messages.content: There's no code, no miners, but already a working product? 🤔
It's currently being coded. They've been very open about that
@Cats see here for the latest info
So no update since a month ago?
@consτ [τ, τ]  and @Cats I see both of your questions, and want to give them proper attention. I have a super busy morning of meetings, but promise I will get you answers by EOD.

Ok !  Meeting ended early so had time to connect with the wider team  to ensure I address your q's as thoroughly as possible.  Hope this helps! 

Votes are weighted by historical accuracy, not just ALPHA held. It’s a similar idea to how Bittensor validators build consensus - influence grows through consistent alignment with the network. Within the sundae_bar subnet validators will normalize outliers and track how each voter’s history compares to overall outcomes, so anyone voting only for themselves or small groups quickly loses weight.

All votes are logged transparently using signature hashes, then decrypted and verified by validators to ensure integrity and prevent manipulation. To specifically work against vote gaming there’s a short period before newly bought or emitted ALPHA gets any voting weight acting a vesting period into the subnet. The longer the ALPHA is held, the stronger the weight multiplier becomes.

Alpha voters who push personal agendas get their weight reduced automatically, creating a natural slowdown that favors long-term, honest participation. If that’s not enough, we could move to a point where voters can post collateral that’s slashed if they’re caught manipulating outcomes.

The validator code will be open, so anyone can see how votes are scored and help improve it. Once the first version is live, we’ll keep adding new ways to detect and counter attempts to deceive the system. The same way Bittensor constantly evolves its validator-miner logic as new gaming behaviors appear. 

As purchase data, transaction data, and revenue metrics start flowing through the platform, we’ll also factor in wallet activity - how many subnets a wallet has bought or sold, its general health, and transaction history. That data will feed back into vote scoring, letting us see which voters consistently align with real-world results and which ones don’t. 

Over time, the network learns who’s adding value and adjusts influence accordingly.

Cats! I understand the questions about building products before code, and the simple answer for sundae_bar is - one doesn't exist without the other.  Our marketplace and subnet are fully connected, so we have to build both at the same time. And it’s very important to us that when the code drops, it connects to a live, functioning economy, not a testnet. We get that this makes for a more complex build, but we’re more than happy to take it on because we recognize the long-term benefits of building a real, revenue-generating business. 

Without getting too into the weeds of the build too much, here’s a bit more context on where we are at:

Agent submission + payments for the marketplace: Complete and live, with today’s payment drop closing the loop on marketplace functionality. We’re proud to have met the timelines outlined in our AIM Admission document.

Brief posting: In QA testing, with a video demo released last week on X if you want a sneak peek.

We’re currently building validator/miner functions and SDK integration, which include agent usage, payment rails, brief creation, and voting. 

Next up is voting and emissions. Validators will process votes to award emissions, and we’re finalizing an open-source emissions algorithm (similar to how X released its timeline algorithm) to ensure transparency and accountability as we evolve.

With all that said, being publicly listed puts us in a unique position as in addition to the Bittensor community, we have a large external stakeholder base that is incredibly excited about our subnet and all feel this is the perfect alignment for us. There’s a lot of hype, and we have a lot of support behind us. Also, it means we aren’t only committed to doing it right, we have to.

Hope this helps!
@consτ [τ, τ] Happy to hop on a call to discuss further if you want. As much constructive insight/feedback is a win IMO!

Hey team!

Would be great to verify your subnet metrics on Tao Revenue to make sure we are displaying them correctly. Who can I speak to regarding this? 🙏

First sentence 

“Votes are weighted by historical accuracy, not just Alpha held”

Accuracy against what? Historical Votes? That’s circular.

Btw this is not similar to Yuma consensus which builds consensus around transparent code — there is no transparency in this scoring process. 

Highly suggest this mechanism is changed. It will not work and you will be gamed immediately by your miners.

Where may I ask questions about (future) revenue split between Alpha token holders and shareholders in your publicly listed company? I don’t expect you to be able to comment on here - hence my question about best place to discuss this.
But also let me dm you guys and let’s talk this through @jill.kenney

Fair point on the recursive nature but the intent isn’t to measure accuracy against past votes (which would be circular), but against validated outcomes over time. For example, if voters consistently support agents or proposals that later perform well on real metrics - usage, revenue, or cross-subnet engagement - their weight increases.

The transparency issue is valid too: that’s why the validator code will be open and the scoring logic public so everyone can see the datasets used to establish this. The goal is to evolve the mechanism the same way Bittensor does, we do have a cold start problem where we have just introduced payments so metrics will have a delayed effect too. 

We heavily considered a Ridges approach as per mentioned in our whitepaper but the complexity of testing an all round agent in code with access to third party services becomes burdensome with current tech. Using community to vet, source and create business opportunities felt the best place to start and learn from. 

Will DM for a chat as we 100% want to get this right.
